    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Structure of an Azure Policy Rule"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Every Azure Policy definition has a policyRule property containing exactly two top-level keys: if and then. The if block is a condition expression that evaluates to true or false for each resource. When it evaluates to true, the policy engine applies the effect in the then block. The entire policy is evaluated by the Azure Policy engine during resource create/update operations (for real-time effects like Deny) and during background compliance scans (for audit-mode effects)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Azure Policy Rule Structure anatomy",
          "title": null
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The policyRule is stored as JSON inside the policy definition. The parameters section (separate from policyRule) declares injectable values that can be set per-assignment. Parameter references inside policyRule use the ARM template function syntax [parameters('paramName')], which is resolved at evaluation time."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "A policy definition with no if condition is invalid \u2014 the if key is required even if you want to match all resources. Use {'value': 'true', 'equals': 'true'} as a universal match condition."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The if Block: Condition Expressions"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The if block evaluates a condition tree against the resource being deployed or scanned. Conditions are combined using logical operators: allOf (AND), anyOf (OR), and not (negation). These operators nest arbitrarily, enabling arbitrarily complex matching logic. The innermost nodes of the tree are field conditions or count expressions."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "json"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Match Windows VMs in specific regions \u2014 demonstrates allOf + anyOf nesting\n{\n  \"if\": {\n    \"allOf\": [\n      {\n        \"field\": \"type\",\n        \"equals\": \"Microsoft.Compute/virtualMachines\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"anyOf\": [\n          { \"field\": \"location\", \"equals\": \"eastus\" },\n          { \"field\": \"location\", \"equals\": \"eastus2\" },\n          { \"field\": \"location\", \"equals\": \"westus2\" }\n        ]\n      },\n      {\n        \"field\": \"Microsoft.Compute/virtualMachines/storageProfile.osDisk.osType\",\n        \"equals\": \"Windows\"\n      }\n    ]\n  },\n  \"then\": { \"effect\": \"audit\" }\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Field Conditions and Operators"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A field condition pairs a field reference with a comparison operator. The field value is the ARM resource property path. Built-in aliases like type, name, location, and tags allow access to top-level properties. Deeper property paths use the resource provider namespace and property name hierarchy separated by slashes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
